\f0\b Snowflake Method Binder Structure\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardeftab720\sa120\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_H::2><!$Scr_Ps::0>
\f0 The binder structure in and of itself is the same as in the novel template, I just added a folder at the top of the draft that contains all the snowflake method documents, or rather: steps.\
There is one document for each step that is recommended. You can see from the icons of the documents that if you follow these steps closely that your story goes from a very rough shape to a very defined and beautiful snowflake.\
If you click on one of the snowflake step documents and you take a look at the notes section in the inspector, you see that there is a little reminder of what each step is about. It\'92s not a full-out explanation and it won\'92t serve you much if you have no idea what the snowflake method is. \
But if you know roughly what it\'92s about and maybe you\'92ve worked with it before, this should be enough to keep you on track.\
One word about  the character step.\
If you go to the template folder you see that there are now two character sketch documents. The Scrivener novel template only holds one.\
This is because this I added this \'93snowflake character\'94 sketch document and it holds exactly the points about the character step that are recommended going through all these steps.\
But still, you have the standard characters sketch also, so you can decide if you maybe want to work with that one also.\
And that\'92s basically it.\
