\f1\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_H::2><!$Scr_Ps::0>
\f0 One more thing. What if you want to compile your snowflake documents in order to export them, for example if you want to send them so someone to get feedback and maybe that person doesn\'92t own Scrivener.\
If you take a look at the compiler by going to File - Compile\'85 you see that I added a \'93Modern Snowflake\'94 compile setting here. It\'92s named that way because it\'92s based on the \'93Modern\'94 compile setting that comes as standard with the novel template, but I had to change it slightly so it would fit the requirement of just exporting those snowflake steps.\
So, what you do is, you choose this \'93Modern Snowflake\'94 setting and on the right side of the compiler window you select the \'93Snowflake Steps\'94 collection. I put all these documents in a collection because this makes compiling a lot easier.\
Now you just compile this, and what you end up with is a pdf that follows more or less the \'93Modern\'94 design from the novel template.\
If you don\'92t like that design you can also choose the \'93Default\'94 compile setting. This will look a little bit different in terms of fonts and also it won\'92t start a new page for each of the snowflake steps, but rather just create one continuous document in case you prefer that.\
Alright, that\'92s it, I hope this template is useful for you and helps you writing great stories and get all those great ideas that you have inside of you out so that many people can read and enjoy your stories.\
